"installation.  For general administration tasks, see the {productname} "
"documentation at https://documentation.suse.com/suma/."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Components"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:2
msgid ""
"{productname} {smr} is made up of various components.  For more on how these "
"components work together, see xref:retail-network-arch.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "The {productname} Server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:4
msgid ""
"The {productname} server contains information about infrastructure, network "
"topology, and everything required to automate image deployment and perform "
"day-to-day operations on branches and terminals.  This can include database "
"entries of registered systems, Salt pillar data for images, image "
"assignments, partitioning, network setup, network services, and more."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:5
#, no-wrap
msgid "Build Hosts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:6
msgid ""
"Build hosts can be arbitrary servers or virtual machines.  They are used to "
"securely build operating system images."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:7
msgid ""
"For more information on build hosts, see xref:administration:image-"
"management.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:8
#, no-wrap
msgid "Branch Servers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:9
msgid ""
"Branch servers should be physically located close to point-of-service "
"terminals, such as in an individual store or branch office.  Branch servers "
"provide services for PXE boot, and act as an image cache, Salt broker, and "
"proxy for software components (RPM packages).  The branch server can also "
"manage local networking, and provide DHCP and DNS services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "Point-of-Service Terminals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:11
msgid ""
"Point-of-Service (POS) terminals can come in many different formats, such as "
"point-of-sale terminals, kiosks, digital scales, self-service systems, and "
"reverse-vending systems.  Every terminal, however, is provided by a vendor, "
"who set basic information about the device in the firmware.  {productname} "
"{smr} accesses this vendor information to determine how best to work with "
"the terminal in use."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:12
msgid ""
"In most cases, different terminals will require a different operating system "
"(OS) image to ensure they work correctly.  For example, an information kiosk "
"has a high-resolution touchscreen, where a cashier terminal might only have "
"a very basic display.  While both of these terminals require similar "
"processing and network functionality, they will require different OS "
"images.  The OS images ensure that the different display mechanisms work "
"correctly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:13
msgid ""
"{productname} {smr} supports POS terminals that boot using both BIOS and "
"UEFI.  For UEFI booting terminals, you will need to configure the EFI "
"partition in the Saltboot formula.  For more information on EFI in the "
"Saltboot formula, see xref:salt:formula-saltboot.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:14
#, no-wrap
msgid "Fitting It All Together"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:15
msgid ""
"{productname} {smr} uses the same technology as {productname}, but is "
"customized to address the needs of retail organizations."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hardware Types"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:17
msgid ""
"Because every environment is different, and can contain many different "
"configurations of many different terminals, {productname} {smr} uses "
"hardware types to simplify device management."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:18
msgid ""
"Hardware types allow you to group devices according to manufacturer and "
"device name.  Then all devices of a particular type can be managed as one."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "Branch System Groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:20
msgid ""
"{productname} {smr} uses system groups to organize the various devices in "
"your environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:21
msgid ""
"Each branch requires a system group, containing a single branch server, and "
"the POS terminals associated with that server.  Each system group is "
"identified with a Branch ID.  The Branch ID is used in formulas and scripts "
"to automatically update the entire group."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:22
#, no-wrap
msgid "Salt Formulas"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:23
msgid ""
"{productname} {smr} uses Salt formulas to help simplify configuration.  "
"Formulas are pre-written Salt states, that are used to configure your "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:24
msgid ""
"You can use formulas to apply configuration patterns to your hardware "
"groups.  {productname} {smr} uses the Saltboot formula, which defines "
"partitioning and OS images for terminals."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:25
msgid ""
"You can use default settings for formulas, or edit them to make them more "
"specific to your environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:26
msgid ""
"For more information about formulas, see xref:retail:retail-formulas-intro."
"adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:27
#, no-wrap
msgid "Saltboot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:28
msgid ""
"Saltboot is a collection of tools and processes that are used to bootstrap, "
"deploy and validate {productname} {smr} terminals."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:29
msgid "Saltboot consists of:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:30
msgid "Initialization:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:31
msgid ""
"The saltboot ``initrd`` is created during image building and is required for "
"bootstrapping terminals."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:32
msgid "Saltboot state:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:33
msgid "The Salt state that contains the logic for the entire saltboot process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:34
msgid "Partitioning pillars:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:35
msgid ""
"The Salt pillar structure that describes how terminals are partitioned and "
"what image is deployed on each terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:36
msgid "Images and boot images pillars:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:37
msgid ""
"When the image building feature in {productname} successfully builds an "
"image that contains the saltboot ``initrd``, the image and boot image Salt "
"pillars are created."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:38
msgid ""
"The saltboot process involves the {productname} Server, a terminal running "
"the saltboot ``initrd``, and the branch server providing the saltboot "
"services to the terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-components.adoc:39
msgid ""
"For a detailed diagram explaining how the saltboot boot process works, see "
"xref:retail:retail-saltboot-diagram.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Delta Images"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:2
msgid ""
"If you have very large images that you need to synchronize to the branch "
"server, you can use delta images to save network bandwidth."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:3
msgid ""
"A delta image contains only the differences between two regular images.  If "
"there are only a few changes between two images, the delta image can be very "
"small.  Synchronizing a delta image to the branch consumes less network "
"bandwidth but it requires some extra hardware resources on the branch server "
"to rebuild the installable image."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:4
#, no-wrap
msgid "Building Delta Images"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:5
msgid ""
"The [command]``retail_create_delta`` tool creates a delta image on the "
"{productname} server.  The tool uses [command]``xdelta3`` internally."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:6
msgid ""
"Use the name and the version strings of the target and the source image as "
"parameters to the command.  The format of the parameters must be `<NAME>-"
"<VERSION>` and they must correspond to the image names and versions "
"available in the pillar.  For example, if the pillar contains:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:7
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"images:\n"
"  POS_Image_JeOS6:\n"
"    6.0.0:\n"
"      ...\n"
"    6.0.1:\n"
"      ...\n"
"  POS_Image_Graphical6:\n"
"    6.0.0:\n"
"      ...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:8
msgid "Then the [command]``retail_create_delta`` command is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "retail_create_delta POS_Image_JeOS6-6.0.1 POS_Image_JeOS6-6.0.0\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:10
msgid ""
"This command will generate the delta image between version 6.0.0 and version "
"6.0.1.  The resulting delta file is saved in [path]``/srv/www/os-images`` "
"and the corresponding pillar file in [path]``/srv/susemanager/pillar_data/"
"images/``."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:11
#, no-wrap
msgid "Tuning Delta Generation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:12
msgid ""
"Performance tuning is possible with the ``-B <VALUE>`` option, which is "
"passed to [command]``xdelta3``.  With higher values you achieve smaller "
"deltas at the cost of higher memory requirements.  For more information, see "
"the [command]``xdelta3`` documentation ([command]``man xdelta3``)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "Image Synchronizing to the Branch Server"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-delta-images.adoc:14
msgid ""
"When an image is synchronized to the branch server, the ``image-sync-"
"formula`` first checks whether the source image is available on the branch "
"server.  Only if the source image is available, the delta will be downloaded "
"to save network bandwidth."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-section.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deploying Terminals"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-section.adoc:2
msgid ""
"This section covers how to integrate terminals into your {productname} {smr} "
"environment.  You can prepare the {productname} {smr} installation for image "
"deployment.  Finally, you can deploy terminals using network boot and other "
"methods."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deploy Terminals - Other Methods"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:2
msgid ""
"If you are not able to boot terminals from the network, you can create a "
"live USB image and deploy terminals using a removable USB storage device.  "
"You can also bootstrap terminals across a wireless network."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:3
msgid ""
"Hardware type groups must be created and images must be synchronized before "
"continuing.  For more information, see xref:retail:retail-deploy-terminals."
"adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:4
msgid ""
"After you have registered new terminals, always check the {productname} "
"{webui} to ensure your terminals have connected successfully to the branch "
"server, and not directly to the {productname} Server by mistake."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:5
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deploy Terminals with a Removable USB Device"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:6
msgid ""
"If you do not want to boot terminals from the network, you can create a live "
"USB image and deploy terminals using a removable USB storage device.  This "
"is useful if you cannot boot your terminals from the network, or if you do "
"not have a local {productname} {smr} branch server providing network "
"services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:7
msgid ""
"You can prepare a bootable USB device with the image and tools required to "
"deploy a POS terminal using a remote {productname} {smr} branch server.  You "
"can create the bootable USB device on the branch server directly, or on the "
"{productname} {smr} Server."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:8
msgid ""
"POS devices booted using the USB device are assigned to the {productname} "
"{smr} branch server that created the USB device."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:9
#, no-wrap
msgid "Procedure: Creating a Bootable USB Device"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:10
msgid ""
"On the {productname} {smr} branch server, at the command prompt, as root, "
"create the POS image."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:11
msgid "You need to specify the size of the image, in megabytes."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:12
msgid "Ensure you allow at least 300{nbsp}MB:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:13
#, no-wrap
msgid "salt-call image_sync_usb.create <usb image name> <size in MB>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:14
msgid ""
"Insert the USB device into the {productname} {smr} branch server machine, "
"and copy the image to the new location:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:15
#, no-wrap
msgid "dd bs=1M if=<usb image name> of=<path to usb device>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:16
msgid ""
"When you have the image on the USB drive, check that the terminals you want "
"to deploy allow local booting.  You can check this by editing the Saltboot "
"formula in the {productname} {smr} {webui}.  For more information about the "
"Saltboot formula, see xref:salt:formula-saltboot.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "Procedure: Deploying Images to the Terminals using USB"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:18
msgid "Insert the USB device into the terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:19
msgid "Power on the POS terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:20
msgid "Boot from the USB device to begin bootstrapping."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deploy Terminals over a Wireless Network"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:22
msgid ""
"For terminals that cannot be connected directly to the physical network, you "
"can deploy them over a wireless network.  Wireless networks do not support "
"PXE booting, so you must perform the initial booting and initialization of "
"the wireless connection on the terminal using a USB device."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:23
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:37
msgid ""
"For more information about using USB devices to boot, see xref:retail:retail-"
"deploy-terminals-other.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:24
msgid ""
"Bootstrapping across a wireless network could expose a security risk if you "
"are using encrypted OS images.  The boot ``initrd`` image and the partition "
"that contains ``/etc/salt`` must be stored unencrypted on the terminal.  "
"This allows {productname} {smr} to set up the wireless network.  If this "
"breaches your security requirements, you will need to use a separate "
"production network, with network credentials managed by Salt, so that "
"credentials are not stored on the terminal unencrypted."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:25
msgid ""
"Before you begin, you need to have created a bootable USB device.  Ensure "
"that the OS image you use to create the USB device has the ``dracut-"
"wireless`` package included.  For more information about using USB devices "
"to boot, see xref:retail:retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc[]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:26
msgid ""
"When you have created the USB device, you need to provide the wireless "
"credentials to the terminal.  You can do this in a number of ways:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:27
msgid "Directly during image build."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:28
msgid "Add it to the ``initrd`` file on the branch server."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:29
msgid "During terminal booting, using the kernel command line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "Procedure: Providing Wireless Credentials During Image Build"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:31
msgid ""
"Ensure that the ``dracut-wireless`` package is included in the image "
"template."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: modules/retail/pages/retail-deploy-terminals-other.adoc:32
